Steps to Expose Keycloak with Ingress + DNS + Static IP

1) Reserve a Static IP in your Cloud Provider (e.g., Google Cloud, AWS, Azure)
   - For Google Cloud:
     gcloud compute addresses create keycloak-static-ip --global
     gcloud compute addresses describe keycloak-static-ip --global
   - Note down the reserved static IP address.

2) Update Keyclock service to ClusterIP
3) Create an Ingress for Keycloak
      Bind your static IP + domain to the ingress.
         Example  Ingress YAML : keyclock-ingress.yml

4) Point Domain to Static IP
      Go to your DNS provider (Cloud DNS / GoDaddy / etc).
   Create an A record:
      keycloak.example.com → <your reserved static IP>

5) TLS (Optional but Recommended)

   If you want HTTPS:  Install cert-manager in cluster
   Request a Let’s Encrypt certificate that populates keycloak-tls secret.

   Or upload a manual cert as Kubernetes TLS secret:

    kubectl create secret tls keycloak-tls \
    --cert=server.crt \
    --key=server.key \
    -n keycloak

